abstract: Stormy news cycles, and an audience thirsty for political commentary, have changed what works on TV at 11:35 p.m.
snippet: Stormy news cycles, and an audience thirsty for political commentary, have changed what works on TV at 11:35 p.m.
lead_paragraph: The formula for success on the big late-night network television shows used to be simple. Keep it light, keep it moving and book a major star, preferably one in the news.

abstract: Ms. Warren had been criticized for sidestepping questions about whether she would raise taxes on the middle class to help finance “Medicare for all.”
snippet: Ms. Warren had been criticized for sidestepping questions about whether she would raise taxes on the middle class to help finance “Medicare for all.”
lead_paragraph: INDIANOLA, Iowa — Senator Elizabeth Warren of Massachusetts said on Sunday that she would release a plan to finance “Medicare for all” in the coming weeks, bowing to critics who have pressed her to explain how she would pay for a single-payer health care system.

abstract: That campaigns are now being fought largely online is hardly a revelation, yet only one political party seems to have gotten the message.
snippet: That campaigns are now being fought largely online is hardly a revelation, yet only one political party seems to have gotten the message.
lead_paragraph: On any given day, the Trump campaign is plastering ads all over Facebook, YouTube and the millions of sites served by Google, hitting the kind of incendiary themes — immigrant invaders, the corrupt media — that play best on platforms where algorithms favor outrage and political campaigns are free to disregard facts.

abstract: When “sewer socialism” ruled during the first half of the 20th century, Milwaukee flourished.
snippet: When “sewer socialism” ruled during the first half of the 20th century, Milwaukee flourished.
lead_paragraph: Since the presidential campaign began, the prospect that socialism would seize the Democratic Party has animated Republicans and created anxiety for many Democrats. Last Tuesday, hours before the Democratic debate, President Trump’s campaign flew a 105-foot-long banner reading “Socialism Destroys Ohio Jobs: Vote Trump” over the debate site in Westerville, Ohio.

headline_main: The City Sanders and Ocasio-Cortez Would Have Loved to Live In
headline_print_headline: The Socialist City on a Hill

abstract: Ms. Ocasio-Cortez hailed Mr. Sanders and his influence on Democratic Party politics at Mr. Sanders’s first rally since his heart attack two weeks ago.
snippet: Ms. Ocasio-Cortez hailed Mr. Sanders and his influence on Democratic Party politics at Mr. Sanders’s first rally since his heart attack two weeks ago.
lead_paragraph: Senator Bernie Sanders wanted a show of force to convince voters he was back from his heart attack, and he produced one on Saturday: At his first rally since the episode just two and a half weeks ago, he reveled in one of the most coveted endorsements in the Democratic Party, from Representative Alexandria Ocasio-Cortez of New York.

abstract: Here’s a rundown of major things that happened in the presidential campaign this week.
snippet: Here’s a rundown of major things that happened in the presidential campaign this week.
lead_paragraph: We here on The New York Times Politics desk had a busy and exciting week helping to host the fourth Democratic debate. Tuesday night was especially frenetic, with the debate, third-quarter fund-raising reports and a pair of major endorsements all in the news.

abstract: Facing a backlash, Mr. Buttigieg’s campaign distanced itself from a lawyer, Steve Patton, who tried to block the release of a video of the police killing of a black teenager. Mr. Patton was set to co-host a fund-raiser for Mr. Buttigieg.
snippet: Facing a backlash, Mr. Buttigieg’s campaign distanced itself from a lawyer, Steve Patton, who tried to block the release of a video of the police killing of a black teenager. Mr. Patton was set to co-host a fund-raiser for Mr. Buttigieg.
lead_paragraph: Pete Buttigieg’s presidential campaign, facing criticism, distanced itself on Friday from a Chicago lawyer who tried to block the release of footage of the 2014 police shooting of a black teenager, Laquan McDonald.
